Consider something like<p><pre><code>    wchar_t buff[MAX_PATH] = {0};
    int (*callback)(void);

    if (NULL == ::PathCombine(buff, /* ... */)) {
      return; // Error, don&#x27;t continue
    }
    callback();
</code></pre>
If this is compiled with a small MAX_PATH and run on a system with a large MAX_PATH, then the system can write a value that&#x27;s too long, overflow `buff` and overwrite `callback`, which would then execute the buffer contents and probably crash. Building an exploit out of this is left as an exercise for the reader (e.g. supply PathCombine with some shellcode)<p>I picked a random API, but there are several win32 functions which accept a character buffer without an explicit size, and mention MAX_PATH in the MSDN documentation.

